Malcolm Gladwell is a Canadian journalist, author, and speaker who has gained widespread recognition for his thought-provoking books and articles on a wide range of topics, including social psychology, business, and popular culture. Born in 1963 in England and raised in Canada, Gladwell started his career as a writer for The Washington Post before joining The New Yorker in 1996, where he has been a staff writer since. He is the author of several best-selling books, including "The Tipping Point," "Blink," and "Outliers," which have all received critical acclaim and have had a significant impact on popular discourse. Gladwell is known for his engaging writing style, ability to make complex ideas accessible, and for challenging conventional wisdom through insightful analysis and storytelling.